<TEXT>
soldiers massacred hundreds of rwandan 
civilians belonging to the same tribe as the rebels who have 
invaded the central african nation according to refugees who 
reached uganda 
but rwandas president denied the claim and a diplomat familiar 
with the area said thursday he doubted the reports were true 
rwandan president juvenal habyarimana told a news conference 
wednesday that fourteen civilians had been killed in fighting 
between his troops and rwandan exiles who invaded from uganda on 
sept 30 
habyarimana also said 3000 people had been arrested since the 
invasion many of the detainees belong to the minority tutsi tribe 
an exiled tutsi is leading the rebel force that invaded rwanda last 
month 
the hutus who make up 85 percent of rwandas 8 million people 
wrested control of the country from the tutsi in 1959 
habyarimana denied reports from rwandan exiles that his soldiers 
had indiscriminantly fired on civilians and killed more than 1000 
people in 10 villages on the border with uganda 
some of the approximately 500 refugees who crossed into uganaa 
on tuesday made the charges according to the british broadcasting 
corp 
there was no way to escape because the soldiers cordoned off 
each village before opening fire a 45yearold man from chonio 
village told the bbc 
new vision a governmentowned newspaper in the ugandan capital 
of kampala quoted a refugee identified as stephen kabarega as 
saying soldiers were joined by civilians armed with knives hoes 
and spears in an attack on tutsi herdsmen 
the refugees said the soldiers accused them of feeding and 
supporting tutsi rebels 
the western diplomat in kigali the rwandan capital who spoke 
on condition he not be identified further said it did not appear 
that government soldiers had reached the region of the alleged 
massacre 
i dont think the massacre happened i dont think there are 
any tutsis or government soldiers in the area he said in a 
telephone interview it may be a rebel tactic 
but he said the rebel incursion could easily degenerate into a 
tribal war 
in 1963 the hutu brutally put down a tutsi uprising killing 
more than 10000 tutsis about 250000 fled north to uganda 
the invaders who call themselve the rwandese patriotic front 
spring from that refugee population they accuse habyarimana of 
failing to allow the repatriation of more than 1 million rwandan 
refugees 
the rebels are led by a former ugandan army commander maj gen 
fred rwigyema a rwandan of tutsi origin 
meanwhile the european parliament in strasbourg france 
endorsed intervention by french and belgian troops in rwanda but 
urged the troops be used only to protect french and belgian 
citizens 
belgium has rejected rwandas appeals for military aid to fight 
the invaders a belgian statement thursday accused the government 
of human rights violations 
belgium will put no troops and military equipment at the 
disposal of rwanda foreign minister mark eyskens said in 
brussels the government will remain neutral in what it considers 
an internal matter he said 
but prime minister wilfried martens said belgian paratroopers 
already in rwanda to help in evacuations might move toward the 
northeastern battle zone to protect other belgians 
