<TEXT>
tropical storm marco toppled trees and power lines as it swept 
floridas gulf coast on thursday and heavy rain streaming northward 
from the tropics washed out roads and dams in the carolinas 
the rain was blamed for at least five deaths in the carolinas 
and may have led to a train derailment 
nearly 10 inches of rain fell in 24 hours in parts of south 
carolina with unofficial reports up to 11 inches the national 
weather service said a hurricane watch was posted for the north 
carolina coast 
bermuda felt the effects of hurricane lili with rain 
thunderstorms and gusty wind 
but while the southeast bore the brunt of the stormy weather 
thursday the entire east coast also could suffer severe weather as 
several weather systems may converge forecasters said 
theres not only marco but hurricane lili a cold front 
all converging on the east coast in the next few days said bob 
sheets director of the national hurricane center in coral gables 
he said lili was moving west and the question is how fast its 
going to recurve and approach the east coast possibly as early as 
tomorrow night sheets said all the weather conditions that 
these are creating can produce heavy rain over the east coast and 
thats of some concern 
marco pelted floridas central and southwest coast with wind up 
to 65 mph and dumped up to 5 inches of rain before it began 
weakening it was downgraded to a tropical depression with 35 mph 
winds by 6 pm edt 
schools were closed in manatee and sarasota counties where wind 
gusts up to 80 mph toppled power lines knocking out electricity to 
50000 people 
at 1030 pm edt marcos center hit land near cross city 
which is about 40 miles west of gainesville the center was near 
latitude 296 north longitude 832 west 
it was moving north at 9 mph but all tropical storm warnings 
had been dropped 
at 1030 pm edt lili was centered about 620 miles southeast 
of cape hatteras nc at 297 latitude north longitude 673 
west the storm with winds of 75 mph headed west at 23 mph and 
was expected to slow slightly and turn to the northwest 
a tropical storm warning for bermuda was discontinued 
sheets said lili possibly could hit land at the outer banks off 
north carolina this weekend but he expected to have a better idea 
by friday 
forecasters expected marco to continue its generally northward 
path 
its weakening but now the big problem is the rain said 
sheets 
rainfall amounts of 3 inches or more were expected across 
portions of north florida and south georgia 
the hurricane center posted a tornado watch for portions of 
north florida and southern georgia through the evening 
local forecasters said a tornado touched down northeast of 
floridas lake city throwing people into a lake upending mobile 
homes and felling trees across railroad tracks weather forecasters 
said 
another ripped through a housing development about 200 yards 
from a hospital near crystal river fla tearing a roof off a 
mobile home knocking down trees and power lines and closing the 
southbound lanes of us 19 
the carolinas had been drenched by the remnants of previous 
tropical weather 
three people were found drowned and a 9yearold boy was missing 
in south carolina after a dam failed late wednesday kershaw county 
coroner thomas horton said the four were riding in a car that 
stalled in high water 
two north carolina highway deaths were blamed on heavy rain 
in south carolina the rain forced the evacuations of residents 
in orangeburg and kershaw counties also dams overflowed in 
kershaw county and two bridges were undermined in kershaw and 
chesterfield counties the weather service reported 
heavier 24hour rainfall totals for south carolina included 950 
inches at honey hill and schulerville with 650 inches at cross 
and bonneau the weather service reported 
heavier totals in georgia included 770 inches at hinesville 
730 inches at jesup and 660 inches at statesboro 
in north carolina a storm total of 570 inches of rain was 
reported at kannapolis and wednesdays total of 410 inches at 
charlotte was a record for the date the weather service said 
fourteen cars of a csx freight train jumped their tracks east of 
marshville nc early thursday thirteen cars and one engine 
overturned dumping 3000 gallons of diesel fuel officials said 
no injuries were reported 
the crew seems to think the ground gave way as they were 
passing over it said norman going a spokesman for csx 
transportation based in jacksonville fla 
officials of the southwest florida water management district 
officials said 35 inches of rain from marco wasnt enough to end 
floridas drought 
it helps but not as much as people think because the rain 
comes down hard and fast and tends to run off or sit on the 
surface said spokeswoman andrea spadafora 
but the rain doused the biggest part of a 40dayold fire in the 
okefenokee swamp ignited by lightning the fire has blackened more 
than 20000 of the swamps 438000 acres 
officials at the okefenokee national wildlife refuge said peat 
moss in the swamp is likely to continue smoldering until the swamp 
floods again 
tropical storms become hurricanes if their maximum sustained 
winds top 74 mph with marco there have been 13 named storms this 
season which began june 1 and ends nov 30 six of those storms 
have been hurricanes 
