chances seem dim that legislation authorizing 
a referendum on the status of puerto rico will pass congress this 
year despite approval of the bill by the house and the support of 
president bush 
sen bennett johnston dla who is handling the senate version 
of the bill said wednesday that time has run out 
with probably only 10 days remaining in this congress and 
absent a lameduck session it has become clear that enactment of a 
puerto rico referendum bill is not possible said johnston there 
are substantial differences between the house and senate 
approaches to this issue differences which cannot be resolved 
within the very limited amount of time remaining in this 
congress he said 
the house by voice vote approved a bill wednesday that 
authorizes 135 million for a referendum to determine whether 
puerto rico should become a state become independent or have 
enhanced commonwealth status 
in order for the money to be spent however an appropriations 
measure also would have to be approved 
the bill has the potential to open up a path that in time will 
bring to an indisputable end the united states imputed 
colonialistic rule of puerto rico said jaime fuster the 
islands nonvoting resident commissioner in congress 
delegate ron de lugo dvi who sponsored the bill said it 
would establish the necessary process at a time when 
selfdetermination is spreading through the world 
bush in a letter to de lugo said i would urge the entire 
congress to act affirmatively and rapidly on whatever responsible 
measure comes before them to call for a referendum on puerto ricos 
political status i stand ready to sign such legislation when it 
reaches my desk 
rep jose serrano dny who was born in puerto rico said he 
hoped johnston could be persuaded to change his mind and move 
forward during the remaining days of the session 
