to consider steps to be taken in the next session of congress 
if there is a determination to continue this effort then i 
expect to resume consideration of the senate legislation where we 
have left off and complete senate action early next year which 
would still allow for a referendum in 1991 or early 1992 well 
before the scheduled fall 1992 local elections he said 
the house bill calls for the referendum to be held sept 16 
1991 or later if agreed to by a majority of puerto ricos three 
political parties the three parties represent the three choices of 
status that would be on the ballot 
once the referendum is held congress would be required to enact 
further legislation to implement the decision of the referendum to 
be ratified by puerto ricans in a second round of balloting 
under the senate bill the referendum would automatically change 
puerto ricos political status it has been approved by two 
committees but still needs action by a third before going to the 
full senate for a vote 
there was no dissent in the house during debate on the 
referendum bill 
status has been an obsession in puerto rico since it was ruled 
by spain after more than 400 years as a colony the island won 
autonomy and full representation in the spanish parliament in 1897 
the next year it lost all selfdetermination when the united 
states took possession through the treaty of paris in 1917 puerto 
ricans were made us citizens 
the island is a commonwealth of the united states but that 
status does not bestow upon puerto ricans all the privileges of 
other americans for example they do not get the same welfare 
benefits as residents of the states and the district of columbia 
they also do not have full voting representation in congress 
neither do they pay federal income tax 
