<TEXT>
safety watchdogs frustrated by alleged 
bureaucratic footdragging are calling for action on 18 most 
wanted improvements in air sea and land transportation 
but transportation department officials say progress is being 
made on many of the issues raised by the national transportation 
safety board and that some recommendations either have been 
implemented or soon will be 
the proposals by the ntsb an independent federal agency range 
from development of an effective air collisionavoidance system to 
adoption of state laws permitting police to confiscate licenses on 
the spot from suspected drunken drivers 
they address safety conditions on fishing vssels and giant 
passenger liners seek new systems to keep railroad trains from 
colliding into each other call for the identification of pilots 
with drug and alcohol problems and seek to identify links between 
fatigue and transportation accidents 
safety recommendations also are made for school buses heavy 
commercial trucks and passenger cars 
each of the 18 recommendations stemmed from the ntsbs 
investigation of an actual accident many of them involving 
multiple deaths 
the boards mostwanted list seeks to speed action by regulatory 
agencies industry and state and local governments 
its a call to action said ntsb chairman james l kolstad 
our mostwanted list of recommendations represents some of the 
biggest areas for lifesaving 
i think on some issues there has been footdragging he 
said noting that federal rulemaking procedures can delay 
implementation for five years or more 
the safety board has no actual enforcement power it can only 
identify possible safety improvements and recommend they be 
implemented 
ed ohara a transportation department spokesman said that is 
being done in many cases 
on the screening of commercial pilots for drug and alcohol 
abuse ohara said i believe we are doing essentially what this 
recommendation is proposing 
the federal aviation administration adopted a new regulation in 
july to identify and ground pilots involved in alcohol or 
drugrelated motor vehicle offenses that result in convictions or 
administrative offenses faa spokesman bob buckhorn noted 
after nov 29 he said pilots must notify the faa within 60 
days of such actions and face revocation of their medical 
certificates which you need to fly if they fail to do so 
kolstad said he believes the highestpriority item on the list 
is the recommendation for the passage of laws in all states to 
permit police officers to seize licenses of drivers who fail or 
refuse to take alcohol tests 
that is the single most important way to get drunk drivers off 
the road he said 
air accidents can be reduced the safety board said by 
requiring an airborne collision avoidance system a recommendation 
first made in 1969 and by installing systems to avoid collisions 
on the ground 
the ntsbs other mostwanted safety improvements include 
legislation to allow alcohol testing if an operator of a 
recreational boat is suspected of being intoxicated 
a requirement that commuter aircraft to carry ground proximity 
warning devices 
sweeping improvements in fishing vessel safety including 
legislative authority to require the licensing of captains and the 
installation of basic lifesaving gear 
adjustable seat belts in new cars to make them suitable and 
safe for children 
new standards to incorporate materials in new school buses that 
will slow the spread of fire 
improved fire safety standards on passenger vessels including 
automatic devices to close doors when smoke detectors are 
activated 
uniform regulations for drug and alcohol testing of all 
transportation employees responsible for operations and safety 
safety improvements in commercial trucking by detecting and 
preventing drug and alcohol abuse imposing medical standards and 
dealing with driver fatigue 
the safety board has made 8200 accidentprevention 
recommendations since it was founded in 1968 kolstad said 81 
percent have been adopted but 1800 including some of the most 
troublesome safety issues before the board have not 
