<TEXT>
nine former kennedy administration officials 
are disputing the governments refusal to release about 700 
documents from the cuban missile crisis 
in papers filed in us district court the exofficials said 
the government has failed to justify keeping information on the 
1962 crisis secret the withheld material includes memos written by 
the nine officials themselves 
they include kennedy administration under secretary of state 
george ball treasury secretary c douglas dillon and theodore 
sorensen special counsel to the president all three served on the 
national security councils executive committee which dealt with 
the crisis 
philip brenner a professor at american university is suing the 
state department in an effort to get the documents on the 
superpower confrontation 
the soviet installation of missiles in cuba pushed the united 
states and the soviet union to the brink of nuclear war the 
soviets eventually agreed to remove the missiles 
the state department is invoking national security concerns in 
refusing to release the documents the agency provided 
insufficient information about many of the documents ball said 
in a court affidavit 
an affidavit by sorensen noted that it is 28 years after the 
events in question and neither the principal figures or 
principal issues of that crisis are still with us 
the state department fails to provide sufficient information 
regarding withheld documents and the reasons for their 
nondisclosure sorensen added 
brenners attorneys the law firm of crowell amp moring got the 
affidavits as part of brenners motion demanding a detailed state 
department explanation of the documents the case is before us 
district judge norma holloway johnson 
the affidavits highlight the state departments inconsistent and 
improper over classification of documents said the national 
security archive a nonprofit group that is doing legal work in the 
case 
the withheld material concerns communications between the united 
states and the soviet union and cable and letter exchanges between 
president kennedy and soviet leader nikita khrushchev 
it also relates to meetings of highranking kennedy 
administration officials and anticipated covert actions in cuba and 
communications from us embassies thousands of other documents on 
the crisis already have been released 
under the freedom of information act the government in most 
cases must identify the documents it is withholding and detail the 
reason 
but the government has failed to do this say the former kennedy 
administration officials 
the state department withheld one document which it described as 
analysis regarding cuba 
there were many documents fitting that description which i 
either authored or received during this time period said edwin 
martin former assistant secretary of state for interamerican 
affairs 
it is impossible from the description to evaluate the decision 
to withhold the document on national security grounds martin said 
in an affidavit 
the other kennedyera officials who filed affidavits in the case 
were u alexis johnson deputy under secretary of state harlan 
cleveland assistant secretary of state roger hilsman director of 
the state departments bureau of intelligence and research leonard 
meeker assistant legal adviser and raymond garthoff adviser to 
the bureau of politicomilitary affairs 
the government also said some of the material is exempt from 
public release because it relates to the deliberative process 
within a federal agency 
