<TEXT>
energy secretary james watkins has ordered 
a new assessment of nuclear waste storage dangers at hanford in 
response to a federal report warning that an explosion could give 
nearby residents cancer 
the report on storage tanks at the governments nuclear weapons 
complex was released wednesday by the general accounting office it 
contradicted a 1987 study that suggested a tank explosion would 
pose little risk to area residents 
watkins ordered a new environmental impact statement to replace 
the 1987 study which was prepared by battelle pacific northwest 
laboratory a hanford contractor 
watkins said the 1987 study greatly underestimated the 
consequences of a cyanide explosion in underground tanks 
the gao report agreed with previous energy department 
assessments that the actual risk of an explosion is low but it 
cautioned that not enough is known to rule the possibility out 
a cyanide explosion would blast a hole through a tanks roof 
and people living near the 560squaremile hanford reservation in 
southcentral washington could receive enough radiation to cause 
cancer the gao said 
if an explosion did occur our review indicates that it would 
be a major accident with potentially more damaging effects than 
those described in the 1987 hanford eis the gao said 
rep mike synar dokla requested the report as part of a 
house government operations committee investigation of nuclear 
waste handling practices the gao is the investigative arm of 
congress 
hanford has 177 underground storage tanks of those 22 are 
singleshell tanks that contain a chemical called ferrocyanide 
added in the 1950s to separate radioactive substances from liquids 
so the liquids could be pumped out no new wastes have been added 
to those tanks for years 
a 1984 study concluded tanks containing ferrocyanide carried an 
explosion risk but that report was suppressed by doe until last 
year 
hanford was created during the manhattan project of the early 
1940s and since then has processed plutonium for weapons some 
plutonium processing continues but much of the work at hanford now 
involves cleaning up decades of nuclear waste 
</TEXT>
