americans out of iraq and kuwait recent state department estimates 
indicated more than 600 americans were stranded in kuwait and more 
than 300 in iraq 
american and other western men are being held in iraq and 
kuwait many at strategic iraqi installations to deter any possible 
attack 
in washington the kuwaiti ambassador alsabah said 
international sanctions imposed on iraq after its aug 2 invasion 
will fail because saddams economy is selfsufficient in food 
i dont believe iraq in the short or long run will be 
adversely affected by the sanctions he told a hearing of the 
house human rights caucus a loose organization of us lawmakers 
interested in human rights issues 
iraqs border with jordan also remains open to truck traffic 
and aircraft still land in amman and transfer their cargo to trucks 
that then poke holes in the embargo the ambassador said 
sanctions will not bring iraq down to its knees and force it 
out of kuwait alsaban said 
he said the embargo was being further undermined by the central 
banks in other countries who are providing credit lines to iraq 
although he declined to name the countries 
saddam husseins policy now is to sit tight to strengthen 
his grip on kuwait and to outlast the patience of the multinational 
forces alsabah said he hopes to break the alliance and he 
believes time is on his side 
it is generally agreed however that the un embargo has all 
but suceeded in preventing iraq from exporting the oil that had 
been its leading foreign currency earner 
saddam seized kuwait in a dispute over oil money and land and 
in so doing boosted his share of world crude reserves to 20 
percent the iraqis have moved an estimated 460000 troops into the 
captive kingdom 
more than 200000 us soldiers are stationed across the border 
in saudi arabia and aboard warships in the region thousands of 
arab and european troops also have been deployed in the 
multinational force standing up to saddam 
