<TEXT>
the editor of the communist party newspaper pravda 
says he has survived a mutiny by reporters who say they want to 
raise plummeting circulation by replacing rambling speech text with 
readable copy 
pravda today published an unsigned denial of reports that the 
newspapers communist party organization called last week for the 
resignation of ivan frolov who was appointed editor one year ago 
the notice buried on page eight acknowledged that the 
newspapers party organization had sharp sometimes tough 
discussions during two days of meetings and that criticism of the 
leadership was expressed 
but it said the meetings did not adopt a noconfidence 
resolution in the chief editor 
frolov said at an unusual news conference on wednesday that 
these people thought they could organize a minicoup 
outside in the hallway pravda writers held what they called a 
parallel news conference about their efforts to unseat frolov 
they said they sought to improve the newspaper officially 
described as the organ of the central committee of the communist 
party 
pravda satirist vladislav yegorov told reporters leaving the 
frolov news conference that the party organization at the newspaper 
had passed a resolution asking the central committee to review 
the question of the editorial board 
he said that 140 workers at pravda who are members of the 
communist party cell had considered calling for frolovs 
resignation but dropped the idea as too provocative 
last year pravdas circulation dropped by 3 million to about 7 
million and it appears to be falling further during a subscription 
drive now under way yegorov said 
he said readers were bored by the format of pravda which this 
week has devoted its pages to the full texts of speeches from a 
twoday meeting of the communist partys central committee a body 
of diminishing relevance in soviet politics 
our readers dont want that said yegorov the most 
important thing is to make it a newspaper that is interesting to 
readers 
the supreme soviet parliament has erased limits on the 
circulation of periodicals but subscribers must sign up this fall 
for publications they wish to receive next year 
yegorov told reporters that subscribers in one central russian 
town which he declined to identify had fallen from 9000 to 240 
in the current subscription drive 
frolov said the central committee told him he could keep his 
job president mikhail s gorbachev appointed him to replace viktor 
afanasyev who had run the paper under longtime soviet leader leonid 
brezhnev 
the central committee will examine what has been happening and 
what we will do next frolov told reporters in a rambling 
hourlong discourse 
he said that all soviet newspapers will feel a shock from 
the 1991 circulation figures 
tamara hlyupova secretary to pravdas editorial board said the 
1991 figures were not available but acknowledged the subscription 
drive is going very badly indeed 
