<TEXT>
the violence of goodfellas and other current 
mob movies hasnt rattled those who crusade against rap and heavy 
metal but in the early 1930s police and concerned citizens agreed 
something had to be done about the too live crew of gangster 
films 
the new york patrolmans benefit association passed a resolution 
calling for a ban on films that glorify the lives of gangsters 
gunmen and racketeers the better films committee of montclair 
nj blamed the death of a 12yearold boy on a gangster movie the 
murderer had seen 
the main culprits were little caesar and the public 
enemy no matter that stars edward g robinson and james cagney 
got theirs in the end who could possibly root for the coppers when 
the bad guys were played by better actors with better wardrobes 
hollywood tried cagney insisted he was sick of carrying guns 
and beating up women movies should be entertaining not 
bloodbaths and when scarface the shame of the nation was 
released in 1932 a grim warning was placed at the beginning of the 
film 
this picture is an indictment of gang rule in america and of 
thecallous indifference of the government to this increasing 
menace to our safety and our liberty what are you going to do 
about it 
but director howard hawks undermined the message the thugs 
stole the show none of the speechmaking by the films police 
commissioner was as effective as watching george raft coolly clip 
paper dolls or paul muni gun down fellow mobster boris karloff at a 
bowling alley a bullet knocking down the 10th pin 
being a gangster was better than being president of the united 
states ray liotta boasts as gangster henry hill in the current 
goodfellas munis tony camonte felt the same way as he stared 
outside his apartment at a neon sign that read the world is 
yours 
gangsters really werent that different from the old hollywood 
bosses they talked tough wore fancy clothes cut milliondollar 
deals they grew up poor and had little education but made it to 
the top through hard work ruthlessness and a strong belief in free 
enterprise 
death was inevitable taxes were not 
because they ennoble energy and because they are low born 
cocky and selfsufficient they demonstrate what one can 
accomplish against all the odds outside the traditions film 
critic neil gabler wrote in an empire of their own his book 
about hollywood 
current mob movies include millers crossing starring 
gabriel byrne as an irish mobster with conflicting loyalties 
state of grace another story about irish mobsters this one 
set in new yorks hells kitchen and starring sean penn gary 
oldman and ed harris and martin scorseses goodfellas 
the highly publicized the godfather part iii again 
directed by francis ford coppola is due in november the 
godfather released in 1972 won the academy award for best 
picture and the godfather part ii did the same two years later 
no one can really identify the first gangster film but dw 
griffiths musketeers of pig alley released in 1912 contained 
some of the classic elements a young couple trapped in a war 
between rival gangs a saloon a dance hall crooked cops and 
gunmen with nervous hands 
the gangsters and the making of crooks released during 
the next few years included such devices as a policeman working 
undercover a major part of the 1949 classic white heat and a 
pool hall where crooks and aspiring crooks gathered 
by the late 1920s all a hollywood producer had to do was pick 
up the newspaper to get inspiration torn from todays 
headlines was how one publicity department described the gangster 
films scarface for instance has a plot similar to the 
notorious st valentines day massacre 
al capone nicknamed scarface was feuding for control of 
chicagos bootlegging operations on the morning of feb 14 1929 
four men two dressed as police officers raided rival george 
bugs morans garage headquarters they lined up the men against 
a wall feigning a routine frisk but instead shattered their bodies 
with bullets 
more and more is the realization growing that pictures can and 
do play an allimportant part in the cultural and educational 
development of the world said jack warner the studio chief at 
warner bros which produced most of the gangster films 
i do not mean we should strive for socalled intellectual 
films but we should strive for pictures that provide something 
more than a mere idle hour or two of entertainment 
this was tabloid moviemaking 90 minutes or less of screaming 
headlines random violence and sex as gentle as a grapefruit in the 
kisser asked how camonte muni got the scar on his face an 
associate snapped in a war with a blonde in a brooklyn 
speakeasy 
darryl zanuck the young production chief at warners was the 
mastermind behind many of the best gangster films including 
little caesar and doorway to hell of cagneys character in 
the public enemy he boasted every other underworld picture 
has had a thug with a little bit of good in him he reforms before 
the fadeout this guy is no good at all itll go big 
warners churned out product like a machine gun spitting 
bullets films were often completed in less than three weeks with 
directors rushing from set to set and writers at times working on 
10 projects at the same time cagney once made six pictures in a 
span of 40 weeks 
some of hollywoods biggest stars began as tough guys and 
molls 
spencer tracy appeared in a series of gangster films notably 
quick millions when he was under contract to fox in the early 
1930s at mgm clark gable was a gangster in several films edging 
just slightly toward the right side of the law as he became more 
famous 
jean harlow had a supporting role in the public enemy bette 
davis appeared opposite tracy in 20000 years in sing sing and 
cagney in jimmy the gent and barbara stanwyck was no angel as 
the star of baby face 
but by 1933 the first run of gangster films was soon over in 
1933 the repeal of prohibition ended the bootlegging wars and the 
following year the hays offices production code called for the 
violence to be toned down and demanded a stop to all the passions 
that stimulate the baser emotions 
gangsters remained on the screen but soon the best films were 
often parodies a slight case of murder reflections on aging 
high sierra or chronicles of a time the roaring 
twenties when silver tongues and deadly bullets gave smalltime 
hustlers the chance to be big shots 
out of this mix of energy suspicion gloom iconoclasm and 
liberalism came not only a distinctive kind of film but also a 
distinctive vision of america particularly urban america 
gabler wrote 
it was a world where ones only hope and only meaning 
lay not in higher morals not in love not in family not in 
sacrifice but in action leavened by a sense of honor 
camonte with a reassuring pat to his coat pocket put it 
another way 
in this business theres only one law you gotta follow to 
keep out of trouble 
