<TEXT>
in the foyer of a new york theater where the 
world chess championship opened this week 100 exotic chess sets 
shine inside a row of illuminated cases 
half belong to david hafler a suburban philadelphia man whose 
collection has been called among the finest in the world 
collected over 30 years haflers 230 sets from 40 countries 
feature figures of jade porcelain glass ivory wood gold 
silver and a variety of semiprecious stones 
theres an aesthetic value in the sets themselves and in the 
art related to it said hafler most people dont realize what 
variety there is and what beauty is available its something that 
can be appreciated even by people who dont play chess 
the first 12 games between world champion garri kasparov and his 
challenger anatoly karpov are being played at the hudson theater in 
new york kasparov won the second game wednesday night the first 
game ended in a draw 
the match will move to lyon france for the concluding 12 games 
of a 10week faceoff 
the collection will not move with the competition 
hafler 71 began collecting sets in 1960 after he bought a set 
for a friends son at a new york department store he returned 
later with his wife gertrude to buy a set for himself 
gert looked up and said lets get this one too he said 
i said we dont need another set she said well you like 
that one i like this one so we got another set and that was the 
start once you get more than one of something that you dont 
really need youve become a collector he said 
hafler later asked us embassies to help him locate dealers 
the designer of specialized audio equipment also scheduled overseas 
business trips to coincide with auctions 
haflers oldest complete set is a 15th or 16thcentury french 
set of topaz and crystal 
he has a faberge original a set napoleon supposedly presented 
to one of his generals and an amber set once owned by russian 
empress catherine the great 
a soviet set made in the 1930s features capitalist pawns in 
chains 
haflers collection is reputedly the best in the world said 
larry parr a former editor of the us magazine chess life and 
review it is certainly first among equals 
the 50 other sets on display in new york belong to george dean 
a doctor from birmingham mich who formed chess collectors 
international in 1984 
although hafler occasionally plays chess he said few collectors 
do in fact some of them dont even know how to set up the 
pieces 
