<TEXT>
the momandpop stores that dot this 
rural state are fighting a ballot measure abolishing maines tough 
blue laws which force most big retailers to close on sundays 
while most states allow local communities the option to restrict 
sunday business maine and north dakota are the only two with 
statewide blue laws maine outlaws sunday shopping at all but small 
retailers but exempts sporting goods stores most notably ll 
bean inc which is open 24 hours seven days a week 
on nov 6 voters in maine will decide whether to revoke the 
28yearold state blue law and grant themselves the right to shop 
anywhere they want seven days a week 
supporters led by citizens for choice on sunday a political 
action group backed by large retailers contend the blue law 
restricts business competition 
the retail federation of maine a coalition of large stores 
began campaigning to change the law several years ago it collected 
enough signatures last year to force the referendum in november 
the leading opposition group save our sundays representing 
mostly momandpop stores argues that abolishing the law would 
disrupt family life force some parents to work on sundays and 
drive many small businesses into bankruptcy 
hugh holmes the owner of maine pride markets in farmingdale 
says he does 25 percent of his business on sundays 
were a really small grocery store and sunday is a really big 
thing for us holmes said when the major stores are closed 
its very important to us because we do a lot of volume 
craig burgess owner of burgess market in bath says abolishing 
the blue law would be very detrimental to his business 
i think the small independent grocers are kind of a dying 
breed and i dont want to be part of that trend burgess said 
the fact is our way of life is going to change said robert 
reny sr a leading opponent and president and chief executive 
officer of the maine department store chain of rh reny and co 
its going to be dog eat dog seven days a week 
but aretas stearns president of porteous mitchell amp braun co 
department stores and a competitor of renys said that the 
quality of life issue thats being raised by the opposition is a 
smokescreen i think givingpeople a choice enhances their quality 
of life 
stearns and officials from other large companies contend the 
current law unfairly prohibits most retail stores with more than 
5000 square feet of floor space from opening on sundays except for 
the period between thanksgiving and christmas when they may open 
from noon until 5 pm 
stearns says exemptions such as the one allowing ll bean to 
operate on sundays illustrate the inequity of the law 
this thing is a patchwork of selfinterested restrictions that 
serve to keep about 12 major chains closed on sundays and restricts 
consumers ability to shop when they want to stearns says it 
is absolutely driven by selfinterest on the part of some merchants 
who have a monopoly on sunday sales 
