<TEXT>
a private consumer group charged thursday that 
electric utilities are underestimating the cost of shutting down 
nuclear power plants and could force taxpayers into another 
multibillion bailout in the years to come 
the charge immediately was denounced by the electric utility 
industry whose spokesmen said adequate funds for the shutdown or 
decommissioning of atomic power plants are being established 
under the scrutiny of both the nuclear regulatory commission and 
state regulators 
but a report by public citizen a washingtonbased consumer and 
environmental group alleged that industry estimates of how much it 
will cost to close plants is far too low and that federal and state 
officials have been lax in requiring adequate shutdown funds 
we could find ourselves in a situation of having another 
massive bailout said joan claybrook president of public 
citizen tomorrows electric users are going to pay 
under federal regulations atomic power plants are considered to 
have a life expectancy of 30 years after which many of them likely 
will have to be closed and decontaminated there has never been a 
decommissioning of a major operating atomic power plant because 
none is that old 
the nuclear industry as well as utilities and environmentalists 
agree that there are many uncertainties in trying to determine how 
much such shutdowns will cost 
the report by public citizen said that industry estimates of 
256 billion for shutting and decontaminating 124 plants is based 
on too many optimistic assumptions and that the total more likely 
will be between 50 billion and 100 billion 
for some reactors the cost to decommission the plants will 
rival their initial construction costs ms claybrook said at a 
news conference 
but industry spokesmen disavowed even the 256 billion figure 
much less the 100 billion estimate suggested by public citizen as 
an upper range ive never heard of this figure i dont know 
where they got this said ronald clements of the edison electric 
institute 
he said that by law utilities must establish segregated trust 
funds for the eventual shutdown of atomic power plants but actual 
estimates of shutdown costs can only be made incrementally as 
plants become older he said you dont want to overcollect funds 
in the first years of a plants operation 
but daniel borson author of the public citizen report said a 
detailed analysis of industry and government documents as well as 
interviews with utility executives indicates that the industry is 
not adequately preparing for what the eventual shutdown costs will 
be 
utility cost estimates often underestimate what it will cost to 
dispose of highly radioactive spent fuel and radioactive wastes as 
well as the decontamination of plants borson said 
while many nuclear plants have exceeded a third of their 
expected operating lives so far only about 35 billion has been 
allocated for shutdown activities and some of those funds could be 
threatened if a utility faces serious financial problems in the 
future 
clements the industry official disagreed he said that new nrc 
rules now being phased in will require that all cleanup funds be in 
separate accounts independent of a utilitys other corporate funds 
the council for energy awareness an umbrella group representing 
the views of the atomic power industry criticized the public 
citizen report saying the consumer group lacks the comprehensive 
financial and technical knowledge needed to produce valid cost 
estimates 
