carl pursell of michigan would exempt from taxation 516 percent 
of longterm capital gains which are profits from the sale of 
investments held a year or longer capital gains now are fully 
taxed at the same rates that apply to other income 
the combination of the capitalgains exclusion and the new rate 
structure would have these effects 
capital gains of people in the highest 31 percent tax 
bracket would have an effective capitalgains rate of 15 percent 
people in the 28 percent bracket would pay an effective rate of 
1355 percent on capital gains 
taxpayers in the lowest bracket 15 percent would pay an 
effective 726 percent rate on capital gains 
couples with no children and filing a joint return would pay a 
15 percent rate on their first 32450 of taxable income 28 
percent on the next segment between 32450 and 78400 and 31 
percent on everything above 78400 
a single person would pay 15 percent on the first 19450 28 
percent on the next segment between 19450 and 47050 and 31 
percent on everything above 47050 
