<TEXT>
americans achieved most of the objectives aimed 
at lowering their blood pressures during the past decade with one 
important exception losing weight the national centers for 
disease control said thursday 
seven of the nine us health objectives relating to blood 
pressure have been met including a reduction in the rate of high 
blood pressure nationwide the cdc said 
in 1979 when the federal department of health and human 
services prepared its 1990 health goals for the nation 
hypertension high blood pressure was defined as a reading of 
16095 or higher 
by this year the government hoped to have at least 60 percent 
of americans who met that definition to control their blood 
pressures with medication diet and exercise one recent survey 
indicated a level of 65 percent the cdc said 
however the goal of reducing the overweight population to less 
than 10 percent of adult men and less than 17 percent of adult 
women was not reached the cdc said 
according to a 1988 federal survey 27 percent of adult men and 
26 percent of adult women were more than 20 percent above their 
recommended weight it said 
being overweight increases the risk of high blood pressure 
which is in turn a cause of heart disease and strokes 
improvements in blood pressure control have contributed to 
a 50 percent decrease in stroke and a 35 percent decrease in 
coronary heart disease since 1972 the atlantabased cdc said 
citing a 1988 federal report 
despite this progress 30 million persons in the united states 
still have inadequately controlled blood pressure 
although comprehensive studies are not complete the goal of 
having at least 60 percent of the hypertensive population in 
control of their blood pressure has most likely been met the 
cdc said citing various studies over the past several years 
however in 1984 federal health officials revised the standard 
for hypertension to a reading of 14090 and progress at that level 
is less certain the cdc said 
a study in south carolina showed 38 percent of hypertensive 
people as defined under the stricter standard lowering their 
blood pressure with medication diet and exercise the cdc said 
progress toward the 1990 goals cannot be definitely 
determined until statistics from a new national survey are 
analyzed over the next several years it said 
other bloodpressure goals which were met include 
more than half of us adults should know the principal risk 
factors for heart disease and stroke high blood pressure smoking 
high cholesterol diabetes 
more than 90 percent of adults should know whether they have 
high blood pressure 
at least half of processed food in grocery stores should be 
labeled with sodium and caloric content 
other goals also met targeted public health systems and 
research methodology 
progress is unknown toward one goal reducing the average daily 
salt intake to less than 21 of an ounce no studies have been done 
to provide such data the cdc said sodium a component of salt 
contributes to high blood pressure 
