<TEXT>
physicians at a conference on suicide warned 
thursday that an economic downturn could spark a dramatic increase 
in adult suicides 
if recession is defined as nine months of rising unemployment 
the correlation is extremely strong between the vicissitudes of 
the economy and actual suicide said dr andrew slaby president 
of the eastern division of the american suicide foundation 
slaby spoke at a news briefing before the foundations oneday 
conference at a midtown hotel on preventing evaluating and 
managing suicidal behavior 
about 1500 physicians therapists psychologists and social 
workers from a threestate area registered for the gathering 
described by organizers as the largest of its kind in the united 
states 
slaby psychiatrist in chief at the regent hospital in 
manhattan said studies on suicide rates during the depression 
found suicides increased most among white successful males and 
black women the two that really suffered the most when they lost 
jobs 
in times of economic hardship he said black women were often 
among the first to lose jobs he noted that domestic workers relied 
for employment on affluent white men who had lost jobs themselves 
dr herbert hendin the american suicide foundations executive 
director said there are no figures measuring the effect of the 
current economic downturn on the suicide rate but he said 
throughout the century the suicide rate went up when the economy 
declined 
in september the nations unemployment rose to 57 percent it 
was the first time since the 198182 recession that the jobless 
rate increased three months in a row 
slaby also noted the suicide rate generally has declined during 
war times the 19th century french sociologist emile durkheim found 
there were fewer suicides during the great wars in europe in the 
19th century 
the us suicide rate rose during world war i world war ii and 
the korean war but not during the vietnam war slaby said 
people feel less desperation when they bond together and fight 
for a common cause he said 
the american suicide foundation said 30796 people 24272 men 
and 6524 women committed suicide in the united states in 1987 
although more men commit suicide more women attempt suicide it 
said 
because men use more violent means to kill themselves than 
women they are more likely to succeed slaby said women are more 
likely to seek counseling or help from peers he said 
but slaby noted that the suicide rate among professional women 
is rapidly increasing 
among 15 to 24 year olds suicide is the second leading cause of 
death after accidents according to the foundation 
the foundation was formed two years ago and funds research at 
major medical centers in the treatment and prevention of depression 
and suicide 
