<TEXT>
the senate voted thursday to ban the use of 
largescale drift nets in us waters up to 200 miles offshore as 
well as their use by domestic fishing fleets anywhere in the world 
the nets which can extend up to 40 miles have been blamed 
for the deaths of thousands of dolphins other sea mammals and 
birds caught in their paths as they float through the water to trap 
tuna and other commercial fish 
the us ban as well as language directing the bush 
administration to seek an international outlawing of drift net 
fishing was included in a bill approved 980 extending the 
magnuson fishery and conservation act another five years 
named after the late sen warren magnuson dwash the 1976 law 
established exclusive us economic control over commercial and 
sport fishing within 200 miles of the us coastline 
the bill extends that control to tuna which had been exempted 
from it in the past because they migrate over international 
boundaries similar legislation was approved by the house last 
february 
the legislation also includes a provision by sen joseph biden 
ddel that would require the development of government standards 
that tuna canners would have to adopt in order to label their 
product dolphinsafe 
in response to environmental campaigns and tv documentaries with 
dramatic footage of waterbreathing dolphins suffocating in tuna 
drift nets when brought to the surface starkist last april began 
publicizing its use of dolphinsafe practices and labeling 
their cans as such 
biden said the labels have been abused and bastardized by 
other tuna canners whose practices continue to result in dolphin 
deaths in their fishing operations 
