<DOCNO> AP901011-0143 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the ozone hole over the south pole this year 
is almost as severe as the record levels recorded in 1987 two 
federal agencies announced thursday 
scientists at both the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administration and the national aeronautics and space 
administration said that the depletion of ozone over the pole 
reached a low point for the year last tuesday 
noaa measurements taken by balloon released from a south polar 
station showed that ozone at 9 to 11 miles altitude dropped to 15 
parts per billion less than 1 percent of normal normal 
concentration is 2000 parts per billion 
for the atmosphere as a whole above the station ozone 
concentration was 50 percent of normal nearly equaling the lowest 
level previously recorded on oct 9 1987 
a nasa satellite measurement made a similar finding the space 
agency said 
ozone in the upper atmosphere is important because the compound 
acts as a shield against ultraviolet radiation from the sun uv 
radiation can cause skin cancer and is harmful to some plants 
scientists believe the earths ozone belt is being erroded by the 
action of chlorine and some other molecules that come from 
industrial pollution the ozone layer over the south pole thins 
severely each september and october creating what scientists 
called an ozone hole 
noaa scientists said that ozone in the air over the south pole 
is normally at 260 dobson units a measure used for ozone 
concentrations last tuesday the measurement dropped to 130 dobson 
units noaa spokesman william j brennan said that the record low 
recorded on oct 9 1987 is 126 dobson units 
sam oltmans a noaa physicist in boulder colo said the ozone 
depletion over the south pole has been following a pattern of 
dipping more severely every other year with the low points coming 
on the odd years 
the low registered on tuesday is a change in this pattern but 
oltmans said it is unclear if the ozone depletion is trending 
toward a new permanently lower level or not 
the pattern has changed for the first time but this was 
predicted because of a circulation pattern in the air currents 
said oltmans 
he said the ozone hole in 1991 may revert to the alternateyear 
pattern that has been observed since 1979 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

