<TEXT>
sen donald riegles campaign committee paid a 
troubled california savings and loan 5000 this year for catering 
services provided at a 1987 fundraiser an aide said thursday 
federal law prohibits corporations from donating to candidates 
for federal offices services are considered inkind or 
nonmonetary donations 
they also are required to be listed in campaign finance reports 
riegles campaign did not report the catering services paid for by 
columbia savings and loan until this year 
david krawitz riegles administrative assistant said the 
senators political organization did not receive an invoice for the 
california fundraiser until late in 1989 
it was our understanding that the bills had been paid 
krawitz said when we were informed otherwise the reimbursement 
was made 
columbia savings and loan chairman thomas spiegel put the costs 
on his company expense account the detroit news reported spiegel 
resigned from columbia last year in the wake of accusations that he 
used the thrifts money for personal expenses 
