the senate voted thursday to begin paying 
nearly half a billion dollars in past dues to the united nations 
withheld in recent years because of congressional opposition to its 
practices 
reflecting an aboutface prompted by the uns sponsorhip of a 
trade embargo against iraq the measure was included as part of a 
196 billion money bill approved by a 917 vote 
president bush last january had requested 93 million as a 20 
percent first installment on a fiveyear plan to pay off the 464 
million in us dues arrearages 
but lawmakers had shown no inclination to go along with it until 
the uns sharp response to iraqs invasion of kuwait in august 
and subsequent taking of american and other foreign hostages 
in addition to the 93 million in past dues the bill includes 
31 million to cover us arrearages for supporting un 
peacekeeping forces in addition to the 91 million as the american 
share for their support in the current fiscal year 
also to support the military effort against iraqi president 
suddam hussein the bill adds 79 million for activating another 
five ships in the us ready reserve force for deployment to the 
persian gulf already 41 ships in the 96ship fleet have been put 
on active duty and sent to the region 
the bill which finances the operation of the justice state and 
commerce departments for the fiscal year that began oct 1 also 
triples to 1625 million bushs request for investigating and 
prosecuting savings and loan fraud 
the president and the attorney general just dont place a 
priority on these sampl criminals said sen fritz hollings 
dsc they spend a fortune arranging stings but they have been 
stung more than 1300 times and dont do anything about it 
the bill now goes to a conference committee to iron out 
