<TEXT>
wisconsins chippewa indians cannot sue the 
state for an estimated 300 million in damages resulting from their 
being denied hunting and fishing rights for more than a century a 
federal judge ruled thursday 
the tribes only hope to collect damages rests in persuading the 
federal government to sue the state on behalf of the chippewa us 
district judge barbara crabb said citing recent supreme court 
interpretations of the us constitutions 11th amendment 
the supreme courts analysis leaves the plaintiff tribes 
without an adequate remedy for the wrongs they have suffered 
crabb said 
the 11th amendment gives states sovereign immunity from 
lawsuits by tribes and other foreign nations 
i find this wholly at odds with the principle that federal 
law operates to provide individuals with relief for deprivations of 
their rights privileges or immunities secured by the constitution 
and laws caused by state actors she said 
the federal government was unlikel to join the case she said 
the ruling reversed a 1984 district court decision that the 
tribe could sue the state based on a federal law designed to help 
tribes resolve treaty disputes 
the lawsuit was to have been tried last month but was postponed 
by crabb her ruling dismisses the claims 
earl charlton an attorney for the mole lake chippewa band 
described the ruling as a minor setback and said the tribe would 
appeal 7th us circuit court of appeals in chicago 
the state still has to resolve this matter the decision 
certainly doesnt address the merits of the case he said this 
doesnt vindicate the past actions of the state of wisconsin in 
violating tribal rights 
republican gov tommy thompson and other state officials were 
delighted with the decision 
the ruling confirmed that wisconsin is not responsible for any 
damages regarding the exercise of the indians treaty rights 
thompson said 
under 19th century treaties ceding indian territory to the us 
government wisconsins six chippewa bands retain the right to 
spear fish hunt and cut timber off reservations on 23929 square 
miles of public land in northern wisconsin 
since a court affirmed those rights in 1983 the chippewa have 
encountered huge and sometimes violent protests by nonindians who 
claim the treaty rights give the states 4000 chippewas an unfair 
edge and threaten to deplete fish and timber 
thursdays ruling is the second setback this year in the 16year 
court battle with the state over treaty issues 
in may crabb reversed another ruling that had allowed the tribe 
100 percent of the safe allowable harvest of resources on ceded 
lands 
she ruled that the resources be shared equally between the state 
and tribe 
efforts to negotiate settlements with two of the most active 
spearfishing bands of chippewa were defeated by the tribe last 
year 
those agreements would have provided the tribes millions of 
dollars over 10 years if the tribes curtailed some of their treaty 
rights 
</TEXT>
