<TEXT>
a case that hinged on whether a 28weekold 
fetus was covered by the mothers insurance has been settled by a 
850000 payment to the family 
american global insurance co had appealed a 1 million judgment 
in favor of sharon and andre bonte and their daughter stephanie 
to the state supreme court 
the case is believed to be only the second of its kind to have 
reached a state supreme court in a similar case in 1981 the 
alabama supreme court ruled that the phrase resident of the same 
household was ambiguous and ruled for the family 
sharon bonte gave birth the day after she was struck by a car 
while walking in manchester in june 1988 the bontes said that as a 
result of the accident stephanie now 2 was born with cerebral 
palsy a nervous disorder usually caused by damage to the brain 
before or during birth 
andrew dunn american globals lawyer said the settlement 
reached last week averted two other lawsuits 
one on behalf of stephanie would have charged sharon bonte 
with negligence for crossing the street where there was no 
crosswalk dunn said the other would have sued new hampshire 
insurance co american globals sister company and sharon bontes 
employer as a landowner because the accident happened in front 
of its offices he said 
more than 850000 was involved dunn said the settlement 
in this case also dealt with some issues that may come up in 
connection with those two threatened claims 
the bontes lawyer thomas craig did not immediately return 
calls thursday when the supreme court was to have heard oral 
arguments 
in briefs filed with the high court craig had argued that the 
fetus was a member of the bonte household and should have been 
covered under the policy which covers relatives who are 
residents of the same household 
but dunn said the usual meaning of relative doesnt include 
a fetus in the womb 
its a contractual issue its not an issue of whether the 
fetus is a person of whether the fetus is alive of when life 
begins he said its not an issue of any cosmic importance 
its not a philosophical issue 
lawyers agreed the case was unrelated to abortion because it did 
not consider whether a feuus has legal rights generally only 
whether it qualified as a resident under the insurance companys 
definition 
