<TEXT>
sponsors of a civil rights bill designed to 
combat job discrimination made lastminute concessions to the bush 
administration thursday in a move to save the measure from a 
threatened presidential veto 
critics said however president bush still appeared poised to 
reject the bill on grounds that it would usher in minority hiring 
quotas 
at least in my contacts with the administration they think 
this socalled compromise does more harm than good declared rep 
harris fawell rill a leading critic as sponsors overhauled the 
legislation 
the bill would overturn six supreme court decisions last year 
and has been the top item on the civil rights movements priority 
list in recent months 
major provisions would reshape complex courtroom procedures in a 
way that would make it harder for employers to defend themselves in 
lawsuits alleging discrimination in the workplace 
other provisions range from a ban on racial harassment on the 
job to a obstacles to reopening courtapproved minority hiring 
agreements 
the bush administration has been saying the bill would make it 
so hard for employers to win discrimination suits that they would 
turn to hiring quotas as a way of protecting themselves in advance 
from such charges 
a housesenate conference committee that had already produced a 
compromise version of the bill went back to work thursday night and 
adopted a sevenpoint package of concessions designed to win bushs 
backing 
even if bush remains opposed supporters said the changes might 
attract enough support for the bill to override the threatened 
veto 
the core of the concession package would offer employers greater 
leeway in defending against discrimination suits it also would 
make clear that nothing in the bill was designed to encourage the 
use of hiring quotas 
the package was adopted 118 by the conference committee 
rep craig washington dtexas who had supported earlier 
versions of the bill voted with critics against it he said the 
changes turned the measure into the hollow shell of a civil 
rights bill 
he said long delays in sending the bill to the white house most 
likely will enable bush to stop the bill with a pocket veto if he 
so desires 
under a pocket veto a president is able to kill bills by simply 
refusing to sign them when congress is not in session lawmakers 
are getting ready to leave washington and get in a round of 
campaigning before november elections 
im not criticizing them theyre senators and stuff 
washington said nodding toward sen edward m kennedy dmass 
but we could have done this three weeks ago 
rep augustus f hawkins dcalif also a supporter of earlier 
versions of the bill said it was time to come up with something 
we hope is more in line with the presidents views 
peter lunnie head of the fair employment coalition a business 
group critical of the bill said after the conference committee met 
that it appeared bush would not be swayed by the changes 
he said there was a white house meeting last week at which 
sen orrin hatch rutah was told point blank the language was 
unacceptable to the president and they would recommend that he 
bush veto this bill 
lunnie said hatch received that message at the meeting from 
white house counsel boyden gray and attorney general dick 
thornburgh 
civil rights advocate william taylor said after the conference 
committee meeting however that it still was not fully clear that 
bush would wield his veto pen when the bill reached his desk 
everybody has heard it from boyden gray some people have 
heard it from thornburgh but nobody has heard it from bush 
taylor said 
rep hamilton fish rny said earlier it was unclear whether 
bush would approve the fresh version 
fish said the decision to go ahead with the lastminute 
concessions represented a recognition by the civil rights movement 
that the choice now was between winning bushs support or coming 
away emptyhanded and refighting the battle next year 
in a sense they have watered down their work product he 
said 
</TEXT>
