<TEXT>
the soviet ruble will be devalued by about 70 
percent in relation to the dollar under soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachevs economic reform program a soviet economic official 
said thursday 
ivan ivanov deputy chairman of the state foreign economic 
commission said the new exchange rate for international commercial 
transactions would be 18 rubles per 1 compared with the current 
56 ruble to the dollar 
the official news agency tass quoted ivanov as telling a 
legislative committee that the new rate would be introduced by 
presidential decree 
tass did not say when the devaluation would take effect but it 
said the rate was calculated on the basis of new soviet wholesale 
prices that are scheduled to become effective jan 1 
the new rate will make exports more profitable for soviet 
producers and facilitate the streamlining and restriction of 
imports which have been growing rapidly since soviet enterprises 
were granted the right of free access to the foreign market tass 
said 
the chairman of the soviet state bank viktor gerashchenko had 
said this week a devaluation was likely 
gorbachevs economic plan which envisions a gradual switch from 
central planning to a marketbased economy is under consideration 
by a committee of economists and politicians appointed by the 
supreme soviet the committee is scheduled to issue a report by 
oct 15 after which the plan could be approved by the national 
legislature 
lawmakers already have voted to give gorbachev emergency powers 
to make the transition to a market and he has begun issuing 
decrees 
ivanov said the devaluation would not affect the exchange rate 
for tourists converting dollars to rubles at soviet banks that 
rate would remain at 6 rubles to the dollar he said 
unlike most countries currencies whose exchange rates 
fluctuate with free trading on international markets the rubles 
rate is set artificially by the soviet government on the black 
market a dollar can fetch 15 to 30 rubles 
</TEXT>
