<TEXT>
democrats on the house ways and means 
committee began writing their own budget plan thursday stuffing it 
with higher taxes for the rich and easing the burden other 
deficitreduction proposals put on the poor and the middle class 
the plan is the most liberal of the burgeoning number of budget 
proposals floating around capitol hill democrats insisted they 
wanted to reverse the trends of a decade in which they said the 
poor got poorer 
contrary to what you hear doing something to reverse this 
deplorable trend is not preaching class warfare said ways and 
means chairman dan rostenkowski dill 
the new proposal would impose a top 33 percent income tax 
bracket on the wealthiest americans ending the current bubble 
in which the top bracket drops from 33 percent to 28 percent 
the rich would have to pay a 10 percent surtax on any income 
surpassing 1 million the minimum tax the wealthy pay after all 
exemptions and deductions now 21 percent would be increased to 25 
percent 
the full ways and means committee adopted a separate plan on 
wednesday containing none of those increases that plan the 
democratic proposal and a republican alternative are expected to be 
debated on the house floor next week 
in the senate finance committee meanwhile chairman lloyd 
bentsen dtexas continued reshaping his proposal in an effort to 
attract bipartisan support 
for example the latest version would limit itemized deductions 
of people with incomes over 100000 a year raise to 125000 the 
maximum amount of annual wages subject to the tax that finances 
medicare and allow monthly premiums paid by medicare beneficiaries 
to rise more slowly than negotiators had proposed 
rostenkowski said democrats were still discussing whether to put 
a cut in the capital gains tax in the package he said if it were 
included it would be less generous than what the white house 
wants bush has said he wants the top rate on capital gains taxes 
levied on profits from the sale of assets dropped to 15 percent 
currently capital gains are taxed at the same rate as ordinary 
income 
under the democratic plan the gasoline tax would be increased 
by 3 cents per gallon that is 8 cents less than the full committee 
proposal and 9 cents less than president bush and congressional 
leaders agreed to during their budget summit the federal tax on 
gasoline is now 9 cents per gallon 
the democrats would limit cuts to medicare beneficiaries to 10 
billion over the next five year that would be 7 billion less than 
the full committees proposal and 18 billion below the budget 
summit agreement 
as a result the democrats would boost the monthly premium 
medicare beneficiaries pay for doctors coverage now 2860 to 
2990 next year and 4620 in 1995 
in addition the democratic proposal would increase the current 
75 annual deductible beneficiaries pay for doctors expenses to 
100 below the full committee and budget summit proposals 
the democratic proposal would also 
increase from 51300 to 100000 the ceiling on annual 
earnings from which the 145 percent medicare tax is deducted the 
full committee raised the amount to 73000 
drop the 2 percent tax on petroleum fuels the budget summit had 
produced 
include many elements of the full committees plan such as a 
10 percent tax on private planes and other luxury items and a 
doubling of the 16cent tax on sixpacks of beer 
the top income tax bracket now drops from 33 percent to 28 
percent at 162770 taxable income for a childless married couple 
filing a joint return and at 97620 for a single taxpayer the 
democratic proposal would extend the 33 percent bracket to include 
all additional taxable income above these bracket points 
