portauprince haiti ap haitis interim government said 
thursday it would allow deposed civilian president leslie manigat 
to return from exile in the united states and run for president 
i am returning to rally men of goodwill to see what can be 
done to save our critically ill country manigat said in a 
telephone interview from new york he said he planned to come back 
next week 
in july the provisional government of ertha pascaltrouillot 
refused manigat entry for reasons of state fearing he intended 
to return in his capacity as president 
but in a communique released thursday interior minister joseph 
maxi said manigat was free to come back 
the government did not give a reason for changing its mind but 
the refusal to allow manigat in had been widely criticized by 
political and human rights groups particularly after two figures 
associated with brutal regimes were allowed to return this year 
manigat was deposed in a military coup on june 19 1988 six 
months after he was elected in an election widely believed to have 
been rigged by the army 
he was the armys choice in the january 1988 balloting held 
after elections the previous november were canceled when ruffians 
supported by the army massacred 34 voters at the polls 
fearing for their lives most haitians stayed at home in the 
1988 race undermining the credibility of manigats presidency 
a former history and political science professor manigat has 
been teaching in the united states geneva and paris he is 
president of the national progressive democratic rally a 
conservative christian democratic party he has repeatedly stated 
his intention to run again for president 
to ensure a free and fair vote the dec 16 elections will be 
monitored by the united nations the organization of american 
states and the caribbean economic community 
at least 20 other presidential candidates have said they would 
run for the presidency 
the presidentelect will take office feb 7 1991 on the fifth 
anniversary of the overthrow of dictator jeanclaude baby doc 
duvalier duvalier fled to exile in france in 1986 ending 29 years 
of brutal duvalier family rule 
political turmoil and violence have plagued this poor caribbean 
nation since duvaliers fall 
