<TEXT>
the two key adversaries blocking senate action 
on a bill to reregulate cable television reached a compromise 
thursday that would allow cable companies to continue signing 
programming deals that freeze out satellite dish owners 
sens al gore dtenn and timothy wirth dcolo reached the 
accord after the bills manager sen daniel inouye dhawaii last 
month declared it dead and buried for the year because of 
threats of a filibuster by wirth and a veto by president bush 
bushs veto threat still stands but gore and wirth agreed 
thursday on exclusivity contracts that would require the 
federal communications commission to determine their use illegal if 
abused 
gore who wanted to give satellite dish owners and other cable 
competitors like socalled wireless cable operators better 
access to the programming produced by the cable industry said he 
hoped the bill could be brought to the senate floor early next 
week 
to those who would continue to block its consideration on 
behalf of the cable industry or the white house i would only say 
that such a move would backfire he said threatening to 
introduce a tougher bill on the industry next year 
both the senate bill and a similar measure passed by the house 
last month would require cable operators to provide a basic 
tier of cable service local and public tv stations plus 
governmentaccess channels at rates regulated by the fcc 
including converter boxes on tv sets and remote controls the 
consumer federation of america the major promoter of the 
legislation estimates the basic service should cost a cable 
subscriber no more than 5 a month 
the fcc also could adjust rates for some other cable channels 
such as cable news network mtv and espn but excluding the premium 
services like home box office and cinemax in response to consumer 
complaints 
the legislation is a response to a growing wave of consumer 
complaints about excessive rates and poor service in many areas 
after the industry was deregulated by congress in 1986 
