<TEXT>
a major coalburning power plant near the 
grand canyon contributes significantly to wintertime air pollution 
over the popular tourist attraction but it is not the only 
culprit the national research council said thursday 
the councils report is expected to be used by operators of the 
plant the navajo generating station as an argument for not 
requiring expensive pollution controls 
the environmental protection agency last year proposed that the 
power plant 16 miles from grand canyon national park be required to 
reduce sulfur dioxide emissions by 90 percent 
to do so the operators of the plant likely would have to 
install expensive scrubber technology critics of the epa 
proposal say that the canyons air pollution problems cannot be 
solved by just reducing emissions from the power plant 
sulfur dioxide can be converted in the atmosphere to sulfate 
compounds in the form of microscopic aprticles which are an 
important contributor to haze in certain atmospheric conditions 
particularly in air stagnation over the canyon and when in clouds 
the issue of air pollution over national parks has been a thorny 
one for lawmakers trying to work out a new clean air act the house 
version of the bill calls for stricter pollution controls to 
protect parks but the senate so far has agreed only to study the 
issue 
the epa proposal for tighter pollution controls at the arizona 
power plant came after the national park service concluded a 2 
million study that purported to tie extensive wintertime haze over 
the canyon to sulfur emissions from the plant 
but interior secretary manual lujan dismissed the national park 
service study as inadequate and asked for a review by the national 
research council an affiliate of the national academy of sciences 
the academy is a congressionally chartered body charged with 
giving the government scientific advice the national park service 
is part of the interior department and a sister agency to 
interiors bureau of reclamation a part owner of the power plant 
the council said it was clear that emissions from the power 
plant reached the grand canyon and that these emissions 
contributed significantly to haze over the canyon marker gases 
deliberately emitted by the plant were found at grand canyon the 
council noted 
the park service study said the power plant accounted for 40 
percent to 60 percent of the loss of visibility in the park but 
the council said it could not determine how much of the canyons 
haze should be attributed to the power plant 
under some weather conditions the haze over the canyon might be 
attributed almost totally to emissions from the power plant while 
under other weather conditions the pollution might contain almost 
no sulfur from the plant but sulfur from other pollution sources 
the panel said 
the park service study did not make certain measurements which 
could have helped resolve the question did not adequately treat 
the conversion of sulfur dioxide into sulfates and did not 
adequately consider the background concentration of sulfates the 
council said 
even with new pollution control equipment at navajo the 
wintertime haze problem at the canyon would likely be reduced 
but not eliminated 
the 14member committee that studied the issue said its 
conclusions were not aimed at resolving the question of whether epa 
should require additional pollution controls at the plant these 
issues involve policy considerations outside the committees 
purview said the panel 
according to the epa the plant burns 24000 tons of coal daily 
releasing an estimated 12 tons to 13 tons of sulfur dioxide per 
hour 288 to 312 tons per day however the council said the plant 
burned about 19000 tons of coal per day during the study period 
and emitted 163 tons of sulfur dioxide per day 
d michael rappaport salt river project assistant general 
manager for governmental affairs said its our conclusion that 
it would be imprudent for the epa to base a regulatory decision on 
findings that have been called into serious question by a group of 
eminent scientists 
dave ryan an epa spokesman said the councils study supports 
our basic belief but said he could not say how it would affect an 
epa proposal expected by early next year 
</TEXT>
