<TEXT>
the government proposed thursday to 
convert 60 billion of its debt to private foreign creditors into 
medium and longterm government bonds 
the conversion scheme was announced simultaneously by secretary 
of economic policy antonio kandir to us bankers in new york and 
by economy minister zelia cardoso de mello to ambassadors from 
creditor nations in this inland capital 
the negotiations involve 60 billion owed to private lenders in 
the us japan and europe brazils total foreign debt is 114 
billion largest in the third world 
we want to prove that brazil is a solvent country that only 
has occasional liquidity problems cardoso de mello said after 
briefing ambassadors of the united states japan germany france 
great britain italy on the proposal 
she said the repayment plan offered three options 
all debt would be converted into longterm zero coupon 
bonds paying annual interest these bonds could be recovered when 
they mature or beforehand at government auctions held every three 
months 
shortterm exit bonds would be available for purchase at 
greatly reduced interest 
mediumterm bonds would be available at slightly reduced 
interest according to the purchasing capacity of the buyer 
cardoso de mello declined to give details of payment terms or 
interest rates she said because they form part of our 
negotiating strategy 
brazil has accumulated some 6 billion in arrears on interest 
payments of its debt to private banks which it has been under 
pressure to repay 
cardoso de mello said this amount would be included in the 
overall restructuring of brazils total debt 
she also proposed separating debt owed by private brazilian 
firms from money owed by the government which would permit brazil 
to immediately restart debt payments 
debt accumulated by private brazilian firms would not be 
included in the bond conversion plan she said 
the private sector if it has dollars available can pay its 
debt when and how much it wants said cardoso de mello 
</TEXT>
