<TEXT>
experts on china recommended thursday that the 
us congress not provoke beijing or raise disastrously false 
expectations in offshore taiwan by suggesting a plebiscite on the 
islands future 
maryland university law professor chiu hungdah said mere use of 
the word plebiscite in a proposed resolution would be offensive to 
chinese officials especially on the mainland because of the one 
china policy staunchly upheld by the united states as well as 
both the beijing and taiwan governments 
that policy insists there is only one china and the offshore 
island of taiwan is part of it 
brown university political science professor michael kau said 
terms such as plebiscite or taiwan independence were too 
emotionally charged for a congressional resolution 
but he added i fully agree that the future of taiwan should 
be determined in accordance with the opinion of the people of 
taiwan and i think even the government in beijing should not object 
to that kind of idea 
maysing yang director of the new yorkbased asiapacific 
council on democracy an private advocacy group took issue with 
the two scholars at a hearing of the house subcommittee on asian 
and pacific affairs 
she testified that plebiscite is not an emotional word and 
congress should freely vote its sentiments about democracy 
rep stephen solarz dny the subcommittee chairman was 
seeking opinions on his draft resolution about taking into account 
taiwanese views on the islands future through democratic 
mechanisms such as a plebiscite the draft said beijings 1989 
crackdown against democracy seriously undermines the credibility 
of its pledges on any issue including peaceful union with taiwan 
while pressing for more democracy on taiwan the united states 
should avoid creating a false expectation of support for 
independence or selfdetermination chiu testified this would 
encourage advocates of independence to move taiwan on a course of 
military confrontation with the chinese communists which can only 
bring disaster to all the people of taiwan he added 
a taiwanese dissident recently freed after 11 years in prison 
apologized to the panel saying that it would be inappropriate for 
him as a taiwan citizen to answer questions about the degree of 
democracy on the island 
shih mingdeh noted however that many people have urged him to 
tell the us lawmakers that there are those imprisoned because 
they dissent in word and thought the civil rights and the right to 
work of those who have been imprisoned over these long four decades 
have not been restored those in taiwan who are engaged in 
environmental labor and farmer movements are targeted by the 
government to be treated as mobsters 
shihs americanborn wife linda gail arrigo interpreted for 
him as he added other people requested me to tell the american 
congress that taiwan is not part of the peoples republic of china 
and the people of taiwan have the right to selfdetermination and 
independence 
