<TEXT>
egyptians voted thursday in a referendum to 
decide whether to give president hosni mubarak a mandate to 
dissolve parliament 
security officials meanwhile remained on alert to terrorists 
threats spawned by the persian gulf crisis 
interior minister abdelhalim moussa whose ministry handles 
internal security said arabs angered over mubaraks antiiraq 
position are threatening egypt with sabotage and assassination 
five moslem fundamentalists were reported arrested in a southern 
city for distributing antigovernment leaflets otherwise voting 
was reported occurring without incident 
the voters had to answer yes or no to the question do 
you approve of the dissolution of the peoples assembly 
government officials expected a comfortable probably 
overwhelming affirmative vote under the constitution that would 
allow mubarak to disband the assembly declared illegal by the 
countrys highest constitutional court and call new elections 
within two months 
more than 23000 polling stations nationwide opened in the 
morning thursday for nine hours 
the turnout in cairo and major cities appeared low 
mubarak and his wife suzanne voted at the northeastern cairo 
suburb of heliopolis their official residence 
in southern egypts assiut police armored cars and trucks were 
seen at key points including squares and within the assiut 
university compound city and university have been for years 
centers of hardline moslem antigovernment agitation 
assiut police sources said five fundamentalist students were 
arrested on campus as they distributed leaflets the sources said 
the leaflets opposed holding the referendum now and attacked the 
presence of american and other western forces in the gulf region 
officials said security was tightened nationwide in preparation 
for the referendum in the past week authorities have reported the 
arrest of 35 palestinians and iraqis suspected of planning 
sabotage 
mubarak has led arab opposition to iraqs aug 2 conquest of 
kuwait 
in addition to iraq some palestinian factions have threatened 
egypt openly with sabotage and acts of terror interior minister 
moussa told a cairo seminar they said they will export 
terrorists to egypt to assassinate public figures 
mubarak suspended the 458member peoples assembly on sept 26 
because of a may 19 ruling by the supreme constitutional court that 
the assembly was elected under an illegal law he also scheduled 
the referendum on dissolution as required by the constitution 
the sevenjudge court said provisions of the law violated the 
constitutional principle that all egyptians must be given equal 
opportunity to be elected to public office it let individuals run 
against each other alongside balloting for candidates on political 
party lists 
using his executive lawmaking powers in parliaments absence 
mubarak promulgated an election law that appears to satisfy the 
courts objections he canceled the partylist method and 
proportional representation and revived the system of voting among 
individual candidates that prevailed in egypt under the monarchy 
ended by a coup in 1952 
the president also redrew electoral districts creating 222 
constituencies instead of 48 the next parliament will have 444 
elected members two from each district and 10 appointed by 
mubarak 
egypt has an electorate of about 15 million from a population of 
55 million everybody over 18 can vote but political apathy causes 
some men and many women particularly in rural areas to neglect to 
register 
