<TEXT>
colombia is trying to repair a judicial 
system made powerless by drug traffickers who often kill judges 
and court officials they cannot bribe or coerce 
president cesar gaviria inaugurated aug 7 plans fortress 
cities where judges can live and work free of intimidation that 
presents them with a choice of plata o plomo money or lead 
the countrys powerful crime organizations are leaving the 
judicial system in complete impotence said fernando carrillo 
judicial adviser to gaviria 
an elite corps of untouchable specialized judges 
policemen and lawyers is to be created and given constant 
military protection 
federal prosecutors not judges will investigate organized 
crime and the identities of judges hearing cases will be concealed 
judges now spend hundreds of hours gathering evidence 
in nine years 228 judges and other court officers have been 
murdered in colombia according to the judges union 
judges who stand up to the medellin cartel run the greatest 
risk in july 1989 judge maria helena diaz and her two bodyguards 
were killed in bogota she had issued an arrest warrant for pablo 
escobar head of the cocaine cartel 
twelve judicial workers were murdered in january 1989 while 
investigating massacres of peasants in northern colombia 
in both cases the government blamed paramilitary death squads 
paid by the drug barons 
marta restrepo a regional attorney general and her bodyguard 
were shot to death in july in apartado a northern bananagrowing 
region she was investigating the massacre of 42 peasants in which 
suspicion also fell on the death squads 
when the medellin cartel declared war on the government in 
august 1989 thenpresident virgilio barco figured he had no choice 
but to resume extraditions to the united states 
the cartel had the government against the wall said 
attorney general alfonso gomez magistrates were receiving 
coffins in their homes as death threats there was no way they 
could have tried these cases freely in colombia 
drug gangs have been blamed in the past year for the killings of 
550 colombians but recently declared a unilateral ceasefire 
president gaviria revised the extradition policy with a decree 
sept 5 that drug traffickers who surrender can be tried in 
colombia instead of being sent to the united states he also 
announced the judicial reforms 
in making the extradition offer and proposing reforms gaviria 
sought to show the colombian people the government was 
strengthening its own institution rather than relying on foreign 
governments a policymaking official told the associated press 
we cannot construct an antiterrorism policy based on the 
justice system of the united states he said on condition of 
anonymity 
extraditions are unpopular and many colombians consider them an 
insult to the country colombia is unable to keep traffickers in 
jail however and extraditions are likely to continue until the 
courts can function properly 
as long as no other clear alternative exists well still have 
extraditions said jorge orlando melo president of the institute 
of political studies in bogota 
barco asked the united states last year to help provide physical 
protection for judges the bush administration sent bulletproof 
vests and armored cars as part of a 65 million aid package for the 
drug war 
a high judicial official said also on condition of anonymity 
a few vests and cars with this you protect an entire institution 
from the most powerful mafia in the world 
he said the united states should offer to train judicial 
workers and added that colombia needs money to build 
maximumsecurity prisons 
on sept 18 a man accused of murdering a leading presidential 
candidate escaped from la picota the most heavily guarded prison 
in bogota 
jaime rueda believed to be in charge of explosives for the 
medellin cartel was one of three suspects in the murder of liberal 
party candidate luis carlos galan whose death led to the yearold 
drug war 
four years ago honduran trafficker juan ramon matta walked out 
of la picota passing through 17 doors that were supposed to be 
locked 
inefficiency plagues colombias judicial system 
for example the supreme court president must personally appoint 
drivers to take court officers to and from their homes this is 
madness said carrillo the presidential adviser 
under the gaviria plan the executive branch will coordinate the 
judicial system 
federal prosecutors working with the police and attorney 
general will collect evidence and press charges judges who now 
gather evidence and act as prosecutors will be limited to deciding 
guilt or innocence 
of colombias 5000 judges only 200 to 500 living in the 
fortress cities will hear cases related to drugs or terrorism 
officials say 
computers and evidencecollecting techniques are to be 
modernized and the government is may establish a special corps of 
the 100 top judicial police 
carrillo said the reforms will cost the equivalent of 190 
million about 3 percent of the national budget and take 18 
months some changes will require constitutional amendments and 
others will need congressional approval 
colombian governments have talked of reforming the judiciary 
since the 1970s but only now does there exist the political will 
to do so carrillo said 
</TEXT>
