<TEXT>
consumers who opt for bottled water over tap 
water might be surprised to learn that their preferred drink could 
be drawn from the source they want to avoid their public water 
supply 
some water lovers may already know this particularly those who 
live in a state like california that requires bottled water labels 
to disclose the source 
but in areas that depend largely on federal regulations to 
ensure the quality of their bottled water consumers may find 
little more than a brand name and a picture of a pristine mountain 
lake on the label 
theyre selling a lot of bottled water because it is believed 
to be better and purer and safer but thats not necessarily so 
all it has to be is as good as tap water said edward zadjura 
who is overseeing a general accounting office study on bottled 
water regulations 
you can have the mountain in the background but you just 
cant say it comes from a mountain or a lake if it doesnt he 
said you can let the publics mind and imagination wander where 
it wants 
he also notes that people overlook the fact that springs can 
be as polluted as anything else 
the gao study was requested by rep john dingell dmich 
chairman of the house energy and commerce investigations 
subcommittee after traces of benzene was found in perrier bottled 
water 
the bottled water industry which favors source labeling is 
careful not to make claims of the relative safety of bottled vs 
tap water the reason people buy bottled water is because of the 
taste said william deal executive vice president of the 
international bottled water association 
but is it safer 
the answer is sometimes it is and sometimes it isnt said 
herbert allen an environmental engineer at the university of 
delaware who helped conduct a 1981 study of domestic and imported 
mineral waters 
the study the results of which were published last year found 
that 24 of the 37 brands tested exceeded us drinking water 
standards for at least one chemical 
but a recent food and drug administration sampling of 50 
imported and 50 domestic brands of bottled water found very 
little reason for concern said fda spokesman chris lecos 
the environmental protection agency sets drinking water 
standards in the united states and these must be followed by 
municipal water suppliers bottled water however is the 
responsibility of the fda which generally adopts the epa 
standards 
if there is a taste difference the reason is chlorine its 
added to public water supplies to eliminate bacteria bottled water 
doesnt contain chlorine either it wasnt added in the first 
place or it was taken out 
often when the source of a bottled water is the public water 
supply the chlorine and other possible organic and inorganic 
substances have been removed 
municipal water suppliers feel theyve been taking unwarranted 
hits from the bottled water industry 
if the consumer thinks they like the taste of bottled water 
thats fine said jack hoffbuhr deputy executive director of the 
american water works association we just dont want them to be 
scared into buying it 
we want the public to know the tap water is safe and they 
dont need to pay 1 a gallon or more for this product unless they 
want to he said 
