<TEXT>
it may be the greatest art museum you never 
heard of 
there is no sign outside the barnes foundation just a small 
framed notice on a gate to a main line mansion that is hidden 
behind towering trees and dense rhododendron 
those who sign in at the gatehouse and pay 1 inside the door 
step into a world of renoir cezanne and matisse that makes art 
lovers weak in the knees 
its a staggering collection says new york art collector 
and dealer richard l feigan its one of the legendary 
repositories of masterpieces of postimpressionists in the world 
they have more cezannes than the met the national gallery and 
chicago combined and theyre all very high quality says gary 
tinterow associate curator of european painting at the 
metropolitan museum of art in new york 
the collection is unrivaled adds charles e stuckey modern 
art curator at the art institute of chicago 
that collection including 171 renoirs 57 cezannes 54 
matisses 19 picassos and several paintings by van gogh seurat 
degas and rousseau is probably worth more than 1 billion 
theres an embarrassment of choice there are so many great 
things said marco grassi a curator in new york it should be 
one of the musts on everyones tour of great things to see in 
america 
but the foundation is open just 2 days a week all day friday 
and saturday and sunday afternoon and is closed most of the 
summer paintings are not sold or lent out and color reproductions 
slides or prints are forbidden 
the collection and the restrictions are the legacy of scientist 
and inventor dr albert c barnes who established the foundation 
in 1922 according to a plan he laid out shortly before his death 
at 79 in 1951 control of the foundation has shifted to lincoln 
university a largely black college in the chester county town of 
lincoln university 
the change has art scholars hoping for a more open policy at the 
foundation 
its phenomenal and wonderful and we all like it said tom 
freudenheim assistant secretary for museums at the smithsonian 
institution but its idiosyncratic 
thats why so many outside the art world havent heard of the 
barnes foundation which is not as barnes stressed a museum but 
an educational institution offering classes in art appreciation 
barnes was an eccentric brilliant scientist who invented an 
antiseptic argyrol a mild silver protein that fights infection 
made a fortune and bought art great art in bunches in the early 
20th century sometimes an entire studiofull at once 
among the treasures les grandes poseuses by seurat le 
bonheur de vivre by matisse and the card players and girl by 
cezanne 
barnes feuded with the art establishment barring critics art 
historians and museum officials and most of the general public from 
his galleries after his death members of the public were allowed 
to enter if they made a reservation 
slowly things are changing the reservationsonly restriction 
was lifted a few years ago as was a limit of 450 visitors a day 
and foundation officials have been talking with museums about 
modern gallery practices something barnes avoided 
prior to this the barnes foundation was considered nearly an 
eccentricity and made no attempt to become part of the art world 
said feigan who is on the lincoln university board of trustees 
barnes put the paintings on the walls of the mansion in crowded 
symmetrical arrangements one wall holds 24 canvases picassos and 
matisses surrounding a modigliani a single small room contains 
more than 30 renoirs 
museums tend to be carbon copies said freudenheim of the 
smithsonian its nice to have a place with real personality i 
think the idea of a collectors personality shining through is a 
nice thing its full of masterpieces its extraordinary 
the arrangements as well as the pieces of decorative iron 
hardware stuck on the walls and the antique furniture in the rooms 
are essential elements in barnes art education program 
that program teaches the scientific analysis of painting what 
barnes felt was an objective way to judge composition color and 
in the end quality 
art appreciation can no more be absorbed by aimless wandering 
in galleries than can surgery be learned by casual visits to a 
hospital a foundation pamphlet says 
a host of publications are available at the foundation 
explaining the barnes way of looking at things and reflecting his 
quirks one pamphlet by violette de mazia education director until 
her death in september at the age of 89 was titled the lure and 
trap of color slides in art education and subtitled the 
timereleased venom of their makebelieve 
he acted more crazy than he was feigan said if you look 
at it the man was brilliant the kind of masterpieces he bought 
could only be bought by someone with an acute eye and brilliant 
judgment 
that judgment wasnt infallible experts say numerous paintings 
that barnes bought as old masters are merely copies 
barnes was long interested in african art he amassed an 
impressive collection and friendly with lincoln universitys 
president he amended a trust indenture nine months before his 
death to allow the school to select foundation trustees as the 
original trustees retired or died by 1988 lincolnnamed trustees 
were in the majority 
dont expect things to change 
first and foremost we intend to be very faithful to the 
indenture and we intend to ensure that the foundation is able to 
carry out its mission as envisioned by dr barnes said richard 
glanton president of the foundation 
id like to emphasize that no quick changes will be 
