<TEXT>
knightridder inc unveils a redesigned 
newspaper thursday that seeks a share of quality time in this 
babyboomer rich suburb 
the news a reconstituted 35yearold daily takes its visual 
cues from usa today with heavy use of color maps and indexes 
eyecatching graphics and clean lines 
in content short trendy stories will be the norm broadsheet 
sections have been reserved for the top news local developments 
business and sports feature articles are offered in a tabloid 
magazine called essentials 
what we did was to take a very specific community and say if 
we were reinventing the newspaper if a newspaper didnt exist in 
this place and we were trying to create a newspaper that we 
thought would have the greatest appeal to the people in this 
community what would it be said james batten knightridder 
chairman and chief executive officer 
while many newspapers have evolved along similar lines in recent 
years this is one of the most thoroughly researched projects aimed 
at baby boomers the population bulge between ages 25 and 43 also 
has among it many infrequent newspaper readers 
people were skeptical at first because they were afraid we 
were trying to reinvent usa today for the local area said lou 
heldman the projects corporate coordinator 
it is meant to have all of the traditional journalistic 
components to do investigative reporting to be a watchdog over 
government and institutions to run stories with an edge when 
thats called for and to not homogenize the writing style 
nearly two years of research went into a prototype intended as a 
model for the company which produces 29 dailies including the 
miami herald the philadelphia inquirer and the detroit free press 
there are 77 million people in the baby boom generation they 
will be the primary customers for news for about the next 40 
years heldman said no one can afford to forget them if they 
want to be in business 20 years from now 
but for decades many newspapers stayed the same staid gray 
shade while everything from television to working women were 
remaking american society 
we dont spend much time in the business asking ourselves what 
our readers are interested in news editor wayne ezell conceded 
we tend to engage people who read newspapers we need to talk to 
the people who dont read newspapers 
miamibased knightridder has done that and thinks it has 
produced a product busy boomers will want 
this one has the cosmetic element to it but the cosmetics are 
not what is important here ezell said we are trying to write 
more about things that people are talking about 
the newspaper whose circulation is estimated at 40000 has 
