predicted earnings would decline again in the fourth quarter 
although many companies are being very cautious and preparing for 
the worst another bleak holiday season 
a slump in profits in the final quarter could be devastating for 
retailers who depend on this period for about 50 percent of their 
fullyear earnings 
septembers results came as no surprise august sales which 
normally are boosted by backtoschool shopping showed signs of a 
spending slowdown 
consumers were already nervous about the economy and the 
security of their own jobs when the persian gulf crisis and rising 
oil prices exacerbated recession fears and gave them less money to 
spend on socalled discretionary items such as clothes and 
furniture 
edelman called the middle east tensions the straw that broke 
the camels back 
the weather also affected sales as temperatures ran above the 
norm and few consumers were in the mood to shop for winter 
clothing 
feiner summed up the confluence of factors as a multifaceted 
barrage on the consumer 
the nations largest retailer sears roebuck amp co said sales 
at stores open at least a year rose 44 percent for the five weeks 
ended oct 6 while sales from all of its stores rose 42 percent 
analysts believe sales from stores open at least a year also 
known as samestore or comparable store sales provide a truer 
picture of a retailers performance than overall sales do newer 
stores tend to have extraordinarily robust sales that can skew a 
retailers results 
k mart corp said its samestore sales inched up 07 percent 
although overall sales rose 102 percent 
walmart stores inc the discount retailer that consistently 
outperforms the rest of the industry reported a samestore sales 
gain of 9 percent and a 24 percent rise overall 
jc penney co inc said its samestore sales fell 34 percent 
while overall sales were off 23 percent 
dayton hudson corp reported a 2 percent decline in samestore 
sales although overall sales were up 113 percent 
limited inc the nations largest specialty apparel retailer 
said its samestore sales dropped 3 percent while overall sales 
rose 10 percent 
thursdays reports also came as bad news for the economy as 
consumer spending accounts for about twothirds of the gross 
national product a dropoff in spending adversely affects other 
economic sectors including manufacturers who sell merchandise to 
retailers 
retailers are playing a totally defensive ball game 
reducing their orders to suppliers said feiner 
the results announced thursday differ from the monthly retail 
sales report from the government the commerce department includes 
sales from supermarkets restaurants and car dealerships in its 
figures which are scheduled to be released friday morning 
in other reports from retailers thursday 
woolworth corp reported a 21 percent gain in samestore 
sales and a 62 percent rise overall 
may department stores co said its samestore sales fell 18 
percent while overall sales picked up 35 percent 
</TEXT>
