<DOCNO> AP901011-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mci communications corp offered the federal 
government a plan thursday to put a hold on telemarketers who 
switch phone customers longdistance service without their 
permission 
this customer switching known as slamming has generated 
tens of thousands of complaints to state and federal telephone 
regulators particularly in the wake of recent advertising wars 
between mci us sprint and american telephone amp telegraph co 
with all three leading longdistance carriers now offering about 
the same prices they are spending hundreds of millions of dollars 
on advertising and telemarketing trying to lure customers from 
their rivals 
atampt has about 65 percent of the market mci about 14 percent 
and sprint about 10 percent with the remainder taken by several 
hundred smaller companies atampt had about 90 percent of the market 
when it was broken up in 1984 
mci called on the federal communications commission to establish 
uniform minimum disclosures in all telephone sales solicitations 
monitor procedures for phone solicitors independently verify sales 
to insure the customer has authorized a change in service conduct 
independent audits and ensure free and convenient return to the 
original longdistance carrier in the case of unauthorized service 
conversion 
customers typically pay 5 to change services now 
eugene eidenberg mci executive vice president said the plan 
will create a national standard to protect consumers while still 
preserving the competition that has brought them better service in 
the longdistance industry at lower prices 
mci said its proposal should supersede a rival atampt proposal to 
the fcc that would require each customer to sign a form prior to 
being switched to a new longdistance carrier 
atampt in january sued mci and mcis telemarketing agent pioneer 
teletechnologies of sergeant bluff iowa over slamming claiming 
the companies had used misleading or false information to persuade 
atampt customers to switch to mci 
mci and pioneer both denied any wrongdoing and the suit is 
pending in us district court in washington 
when the lawsuit was filed mci said 100000 atampt customers a 
week were switching to mci because it offered better service but 
atampts suit said mci agents were telling atampt customers that mci 
was merging with atampt or that atampt was going out of business 
telemarketers according to industry analysts often prey on the 
elderly the hard of hearing or those who dont speak english well 
fcc rules now require only that longdistance carriers provide 
local phone companies with written verification from customers if 
the local phone company asks for proof 
the house government operations subcommittee on government 
information justice and agriculture will hold hearings on slamming 
next wednesday according to aides to the subcommittees chairman 
rep bob wise dwva 
