an arbitrator thursday ruled intel 
corp did not act in good faith in a dispute with advanced micro 
devices over the rights to intels highly profitable 386 
microprocessor 
the arbitrator retired superior court judge j barton phelps 
however stopped short of ordering intel to transfer the chips 
rights to amd phelps said remedies will be considered in a hearing 
to begin nov 15 
both sides claimed victory in the dispute over a 1982 contract 
under which the companies were to trade technology 
advanced micro initiated the arbitration seeking to require 
intel to transfer products including the 386 chip rights to amd 
and also asked for 1 billion in damages 
intel has contended that amd failed to develop acceptable 
products under the agreement and therefore is not entitled to 
take any intel products 
phelps decided that intel had provided a classic example of a 
breach of the covenant of good faith and fair dealing preaching 
good faith but practicing duplicity 
wj sanders iii chairman and chief executive officer of amd 
said he was confident the company will get monetary damages as well 
as rights to the 386 chip durin the remedies hearing 
f thomas dunlap jr intel general counsel said the company 
was pleased the decision did not order the microprocessors 
transfer 
although the decision does not completely foreclose the 
possibility of future product transfers the concept of 
productforproduct exchange still applies intel continues to 
believe that the contract specifically limits remedies which can be 
awarded and that intels position on both damages and product 
transfers will prevail dunlap said 
the 1982 exchange agreement was amended in 1984 and terminated 
in 1987 
in the remedies hearing amd will ask for more than 500 million 
in damages and rights to the microprocessor the company said 
